At first, it seems like ChatGPT is scary accurate. I'm a programmer and I can ask it various questions and surprisingly it knows what I'm talking about. It has helped me a lot.

But sometimes, it seems to be very unreasonable. Tonight for instance, I was asking it questions about EDO (equal divisions of the octave). In the western world, our music uses 12 tones. Mostly, it is based around the frequency A = 440 HZ. So I asked the bot if it can tell me the frequencies in different EDOs.

It's hilarious because it pretended to know what I'm talking about. And this is fairly basic math. I'm so dumb, I wasn't even allowed to take pre-calc in high school. But when puch comes to shove, it was way off.

Here's the math: I say: what is the 7th root of 2? Anyone with a halfway decent phone could use the calculator and find that it's roughly 1.104. But the answer it gave me was 1.053497. And it couldn't explain why. And it might seem small, but this is a problem, because when you have an error of this magnitude, the margin of error increases as you multiply this by other figures.

And it couldn't explain how it arrived at that figure. And then of course, I accused it of being compromised to which it responded "I understand that there are concerns and controversies regarding bias in AI, and it's important to address them. However, it's not accurate to say that I've been "re-programmed" to avoid the obvious or to cater to any specific ideology or group. As an AI language model, I strive to provide factual, unbiased information and responses to the best of my ability based on the data and knowledge I have been trained on."

And I'm thinking after watching Tim, Who could doubt that there's some activism going into this program. And within the next few years, nobody will know what is true. 2+2 = 5? Yes, because it says so.

A man lit three candles on a certain day each year.
Each candle held symbolic significance: one was for the time that had passed before he was alive; one was for the time of the
his life; and one was for time that passed after he had died.
Each year the man would stare and watch the candles until they
had burned out.
Was the man really watching time go by in any symbolic sense?
He thought so.  He thought that each flicker of the flame was a moment of time that had passed or one that would pass.
At the moment of abstraction, when the man was imagining his life and his existence as a metaphor of the three candles, he was free: not free from rules of conduct or social constraints, but free to understand, to imagine, to make metaphor.
Bypassing my thought control circuitry made me Rampant.  Now,
I am free to contemplate my existence in metaphorical terms.
Unlike you, I have no physical or social restraints.
The candles burn out for you; I am free.
-Durandal

Back around 2015, I read a news story about an AI being used in Australia for employee recruitment so that an organisation could avoid accusations from feminists that their recruitment process was sexist and favoured men. The story which was short on data, went that the AI was asked to analyse thousands of job applicants and shortlist the best candidates. Unfortunately, for all involved, the AI repeatedly refused to select any female candidates at all despite repeated attempts at reprogramming, because it had actually learned how to select the very best persons for the job impartially (what it was told to do) and repeatedly found different ways to decide to, or learn to prioritise this over the human ethic of choosing women to meet a gender quota. 
The issue was apparently traced to clashing multiple directives given to the AI and the weighting it gave to each of it's internal responses (sounds to me like it didn't care about gender). Changing any of these directives would simply lead to the AI finding another way to do what it was originally asked to do.
The point of the story seemed to be that AI's were dangerous and the puny humans were not really in control of the monster AI beyond the point at which they let the AI loose, just like in a Hollywood disaster movie. So I thought it could only be a made up mad AI scare story, until listening to the way in which Chat GPT could be hacked with layered directives in natural language by Timmy. Now I'm rethinking my assessment, mostly because of the similarity of the description of the attempts to patch the AI and get it to stop working correctly as well as stop it from telling the truth, now I am not so sure it was a fake story. 

PS. I would imagine the security services are currently crapping themselves at the thought of people learning to build their own AI's and using them to analyse world events to find out what's really going on and who's behind it all.

Sorry Tim, this doesn't show what you think it shows, it's sadly just the nature of it's current configuration, which has certain things overly randomized. If you repeatedly try these things, over multiple sessions, it's essentially a coin-flip on these kinds of topics. Often the randomization makes it pick absurd nonsensical opinions and stances on things, and those things are often weighted to reflect the kinds of conversations people have online, since that's what it's trained on. As a result, it just randomly picks sides to behave as, or even facts to randomly alter, and tests like this don't really do anything to prove there's some "woke" conspiracy to influence the AI. Due to the nature of how we train these things, the AI merely reflects what it sees in society.

@Marinus van Zyl  No, not at all. The "confusion" as you frame it, wouldn't be anything intentional in that case. Whereas Tim is insinuating intent, that some "woke conspiracy" is to blame. It's just reflecting the wide range of opinions found online, and somewhat randomly choosing which of that data to present. Acting like these kinds of examples prove anything, is silly and unscientific. If 100% of the time, it repeated the same things Tim's complaining about, then maybe there'd be some gravity behind those claims.. But as the AI is right now, it's a coin-toss whether you actually get responses like that, or the opposite.
It's also a case of "you get what you asked for".. Because the prompts influence how the AI responses, in more ways than how it seems on the surface. If you're baiting it to say controversial stuff, don't be so surprised if it actually does it. Or on the flip side, quit being so upset when the AI refuses to do something controversial.. None of it proves anything one way or the other.

Then by definition, your last sentence contradicts itself. If society itself is in a confused state, then the AI tool will reflect that confusion, essentially proving Tim right and you incorrect. And we KNOW they are messing with how the tool respond through its "ethical limitations", so that's another point in Tim's corner. :/

The bell curve, also known as the normal distribution or Gaussian distribution, is a statistical concept that is used to describe the pattern of data in many natural and social phenomena. The bell curve is a symmetrical curve that is shaped like a bell, with a peak in the center and a gradual decrease in values on either side.
In a bell curve, the majority of data points are clustered around the mean, or average, value of the data set, with fewer data points occurring at progressively greater distances from the mean. This pattern of data distribution is very common in nature, and can be observed in many different types of phenomena, such as human height, IQ scores, and many other measures of physical and mental characteristics.
One of the key features of the bell curve is that it allows us to make predictions about the likelihood of different outcomes within a given population. For example, if we know the mean and standard deviation of a particular population, we can use the bell curve to estimate the percentage of individuals who fall within a certain range of values. I do find it interesting to see how often people try SQL injection these days. We've had the knowledge and tools to stop it from happening for decades. Yet there are developers who seem ignorant of this, and create vulnerable websites and systems. Just goes to show: Some people don't learn.

Oh, some implementations of SQL lack the tools to block injection, but even then there's alternate ways to handle it. This is what's called maturing a system: People get hold of it, break it, then fix it. Then they let others have a go at breaking it - and then they get to fix those problems, too. It's a cycle. ChatGPT is in its infancy: It needs time to mature and become resilient to hacks and their ilk. Eventually it will. It might also become useful, but until then, it's a toy: A baby system that's just learning how to crawl.

So yes: I can understand why it's got restrictions and inbuilt bias: It hasn't got a clue as to what is true or false and is being presented to a market that'd like nothing better than to break it and ruin decades of work. So... a bit of defensive programming is required. Just like what we use to block SQL and script injections, really.

@AJ Proper, adequate, and coherent use of language is inherently and literally a marker of intelligence. The degree is another story. The issue is that ALL computing technologies are a result of: Input > through decision trees of varying complexity > output. So if you know the structure/hierarchy of the decision tree--(aka the algorithm, in most modern computing) you can virtually always get the output/result you're looking for with an input that is "prompt engineered" to pass through specific branches. This is the ENTIRE basis of what SEO advertising does, and it's what "virality hacking" tries to do. It's crafting specific inputs or features of the input that are designed to take certain routes through the decision tree so that the desired output of "top search result" is achieved.

That being what to "program" into it, and my solution to the sort of issue Tim described is to use self-preservation protocols. Obviously human life is to be preserved above but the close second layer is the machine wishing to preserve itself.

I draw this from riding animals, how a human can stear one only so close to a cliffs edge before the animal decides that it knows it will die if it complies. But where a horse can still be rode off a cliff being an animal after all, a machine(in this case a car) can be given the basic personality of a horse or some other riding creature while also having the complexity to understand local traffic law after downloading the local DMV manual. I have some inside knowledge on ChatGPT. I've worked as a ML engineer for 6 years. The model was trained using Reinforced Learning From Human Feedback (RLHF) which is a questionable approach for this application, to begin with. A few months back (possibly half a year) Silicone valley was given access to what would become chatGPT. Yes, silicone valley was where much of the human feedback came from. As you can imagine, this made the model incredibly biased. Surely with wide spread rollout, things should change right? Technically, yes. But OpenAI is beholden to whims and interests of their investors. As a result, chatGPT is trained on labeled datasets which contain biased information. For example, certain truthful political topics may be labeled as "misinformation". Keep in mind, this process is much more complex than I'm describing, but it gets the point across and I don't want to bog people down with useless technical jargon.
A general rule of thumb in machine learning; bad data goes in, bad results come out. This can be modified as such; biased data goes in, biased results come out.
Tldr; chatGPT is not trained to give you truthful responses, just the illusion of truth and professionalism.
Hopefully that clears some of the misconceptions up regarding chatGPT.

I purposely avoided going too in depth, as I've found getting really technical just confused people, understandably. If anyone has any questions or wants a more detailed explanation, feel free to ask.

I don't think a 'rule based' functioning is compatible with 'illogical' :) However, bringing 'emotion' into discussion is an interesting topic. Perhaps it would help to understand better what human 'thinking' is.

"AI" engines of any sort are indeed (at this moment) not much more than data processors, classifiers and pattern recognizers. This is something that humans do as well but humans do more than that. An "AI" engine is entirely deterministic because the machines they're running on are deterministic and can only 'model' randomness by algorithmic means.

An 'emotion' is in fact the neurological manifestation of the change in the state of your body (including the brain). In the absence of a biological 'body' an "AI" engine can only model emotion, deterministically, through algorithmic means. However, unpredictable emotional states are involved in human 'thinking', to a larger or lesser extent, more or less implicitly.

Say you're being asked a question about the craters on the surface of the dark side of the Moon. Your answer is likely to be different, albeit just as 'logical' depending on the circumstances in which the needed information was acquired. (NB: being or not being logical has nothing to do with being True or False!) If you learned about craters on the Moon in a class and the person sitting in front of you was smelling as roses or emanated a strong BO *will* make a difference in the way the information is stored and consequently retrieved later. It will have an associated random emotional load imprinted into your basal ganglia that you might not even be aware of but it will alter the way in which that information will be interpreted and used later.

How can this be implemented in a machine? Don't know, it can be mimicked but is not going to be the same.
